<doc id="48140" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=48140" title="Air New Zealand Screen Awards winners announced">
<h1>Air New Zealand Screen Awards winners announced</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Air%20New%20Zealand%20Screen%20Awards%20winners%20announced&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 
The winners of the annual 2006 &lt;a href="w%3AAir%20New%20Zealand"&gt;Air New Zealand&lt;/a&gt; Screen Awards were announced on Thursday, 24 August night.

The movie: ♡❤&lt;a href="w%3AThe%20World%27s%20Fastest%20Indian"&gt;The World's Fastest Indian&lt;/a&gt;♡❤, about an &lt;a href="w%3AInvercargill"&gt;Invercargill&lt;/a&gt; motorcycle enthusiast who set a world speed record in 1967 on his &lt;a href="w%3AIndian%20%28motorcycle%29"&gt;Indian motorcycle&lt;/a&gt;, won altogether seven awards. The awards were for best-
<ul>
BULLET::::- Director, &lt;a href="w%3ARoger%20Donaldson"&gt;Roger Donaldson&lt;/a&gt;,
BULLET::::- Leading actor, &lt;a href="w%3AAnthony%20Hopkins"&gt;Sir Anthony Hopkins&lt;/a&gt;,
BULLET::::- Film, Gary Hannam and Roger Donaldson (producers),
BULLET::::- Screenplay, Roger Donaldson,
BULLET::::- Editing, John Gilbert,
BULLET::::- Sound, Tim Prebble, Gethin Creagh and Michael Hedges and
BULLET::::- Production design, J Dennis Washington &amp; Rob Gillies.
</ul>
However both Donaldson and Hopkins were not present at the ceremony to receive their awards.

John Gilbert, ♡❤The World's Fastest Indian♡❤ editor, said: "The movie is successful because people can relate to the main character."

The film ♡❤&lt;a href="w%3ANo.%202"&gt;No. 2&lt;/a&gt;♡❤ won four awards, they were for best:
<ul>
BULLET::::- Actress, &lt;a href="w%3ARuby%20Dee"&gt;Ruby Dee&lt;/a&gt;,
BULLET::::- Supporting actor, Rene Naufahu,
BULLET::::- Supporting actress, Mia Blake and
BULLET::::- Original music, &lt;a href="w%3ADon%20McGlashan"&gt;Don McGlashan&lt;/a&gt;.
</ul>
Ruby Dee, American actress was also absent from the ceremony.

The ♡❤River Queen♡❤ scored two awards, including best:
<ul>
BULLET::::- Cinematography, Alun Bollinger and
BULLET::::- Costume design, Barbara Darragh.

</ul>
In the television section the ♡❤&lt;a href="w%3AThe%20Insider%27s%20Guide%20To%20Love"&gt;The Insider's Guide To Love&lt;/a&gt;♡❤ won six awards, including the best:
<ul>
BULLET::::- Contribution to design, Nic Smillie,
BULLET::::- Actor, Gareth Reeves,
BULLET::::- Actress, Kate Elliott,
BULLET::::- Director in a drama/comedy programme, Nathan Price,
BULLET::::- Camerawork in a drama, Simon Baumfield and
BULLET::::- Original music, David Long.

</ul>
Television series ♡❤Interrogation♡❤ won three awards, for best:
<ul>
BULLET::::- Supporting actress, Claire Chitham,
BULLET::::- Script for a single episode of a drama series or serial, Fiona Samuel and
BULLET::::- Editing in a Drama programme, Lisa Hough.

</ul>
Television comedy series ♡❤&lt;a href="w%3Abro%27Town"&gt;bro'Town&lt;/a&gt;♡❤ won three awards for best:
<ul>
