<doc id="48863" url="https://en.wikinews.org/wiki?curid=48863" title="Canadian union upset over Scugog councilor lowering flag">
<h1>Canadian union upset over Scugog councilor lowering flag</h1>
&lt;strong class="published"&gt;&lt;span id="publishDate" class="value-title" title=""&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span class="Z3988" style="display:none" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:User%3ADendodge&amp;rft_id=info:sid/en.wikinews.org:&amp;rft.atitle=Canadian%20union%20upset%20over%20Scugog%20councilor%20lowering%20flag&amp;rft.jtitle=Wikinews&amp;rft.date=&amp;rft.aucorp=Wikinews+contributors&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.rights=CC-BY+2.5&amp;rft.identifier=&amp;rft.artnum="&gt; &lt;/span&gt; 
A &lt;a href="w%3AScugog%2C%20Ontario"&gt;Scugog Township&lt;/a&gt; councillor Lynn Philip Hodgson lowered the town hall flag to half mast following the death of an Edmonton-based medic, Cpl. Andrew James Eykelenboom, who was killed in a fiery suicide attack south of Kandahar.

It is part of a unionized municipal employee's contract to raise and lower the Canadian flag on township properties, a role supposedly written into &lt;a href="w%3ACanadian%20Union%20of%20Public%20Employees"&gt;CUPE&lt;/a&gt; Local 1785-01's collective agreement with the municipality northeast of &lt;a href="w%3AWhitby%2C%20Ontario"&gt;Whitby, Ontario&lt;/a&gt;.

"I can't talk for the union, but I think on this one, maybe they could have passed," &lt;a href="w%3ARoyal%20Canadian%20Legion"&gt;Royal Canadian Legion&lt;/a&gt; branch 419 president Lucy Wilson said. 

The municipal office in &lt;a href="w%3APort%20Perry%2C%20Ontario"&gt;Port Perry, Ontario&lt;/a&gt; was closed and no union employees were on site.

"It only takes two minutes to lower a flag," said Hodgson.

His position as a town councillor is restricting him from commenting further until the union is dealt with.

